%U A395034 13327293899442,95234646907040,696070597359534,5063050890337060,37253184779069542,274174108861808900
%N A395034 a(n) is the number of different ways for two particles to reach each other's starting corner on a triangular grid of side n units while changing direction at each grid point, such that the distance between each particle and its own starting corner is always increasing, and the two particles never meet.
%C A395034 Both particles start at the same time and move with the same constant speed along the grid lines of the triangular grid.
%C A395034 Let ABC be an equilateral triangular grid of side n containing n^2 unit equilateral triangles. X axis is defined along AB and Y axis is defined along AC such that starting point A has coordinates (0,0), finishing point B has coordinates (n,0) and C is at (0,n).
%C A395034 A grid point (x,y) on a path of the moving point P satisfies the following conditions when generating string of coordinates of grid points on a valid path.
%C A395034 x + y <= n, y <= n/2 and x^2 + y^2 + x*y should increase when moving to the next grid point. As P moves from one grid point to the next x remains unchanged or increased by 1 unit. If x does not change y should increase by 1 unit, if x increases by 1 unit y should remain unchanged or decreased by 1 unit. Any three consecutive grid points of a string cannot have same x coordinates or same y coordinates.
%C A395034 Each of P-path gives a unique Q-path by transforming a grid point (h, k) on P-path into (n - h - k, k) on Q-path. A P-path and a Q-path do not meet if r-th coordinate of P is different from r-th coordinate of Q. The r-th and (r+1)-th coordinates of P must not appear swapped in Q at positions r and r+1. Paths do not need to have equal length.
%H A395034 Janaka Rodrigo, <a href="/A395034/a395034.txt">Python Code for pairs of grid paths</a>
%e A395034 n = 2 has 2 different ways of reaching to other's starting corner:
%e A395034 Grid paths from A to B:
%e A395034   P1:{(0,0), (0,1), (1,1), (2,0)},
%e A395034   P2:{(0,0), (1,0), (1,1), (2,0)}.
%e A395034 Grid paths from B to A:
%e A395034   Q1:{(2,0), (1,0), (0,1), (0,0)},
%e A395034   Q2:{(2,0), (1,1), (0,1), (0,0)}.
%e A395034 Set of valid pairs of grid paths:
%e A395034   {(P1,Q1), (P2,Q2)}
%e A395034 Therefore a(2) = 2.
%Y A395034 Cf. A394097, A394698.
%K A395034 nonn,walk,new
%O A395034 1,2
